data.title: Santa Barbara and San Luis Obispo County Scanner List
data.text:
VHF and UHF Frequency List for

Santa Barbara and San Luis Obispo Counties, California

December, 2007

I've finally gotten around to doing an update. Most of the work so far has been migrating from a DOS-based database to a Windows-based spreadsheet on my new machine. I now have one less excuse for not doing more regular updating.

Note: This file is very long (over 1000 lines) and 80 columns wide. It may be more convenient to save it to an ASCII file to view off-line. If this is too big, how about a smaller list? If you don't like my list, try someone else's.

This list is sorted by agency. It is also available sorted by frequency, in dBASE .DBF format and in Excel .XLS format.

(You may need to right-click on this link and Save As, or the Mac equivalent, to download it.)

This frequency list is copyrighted. You may use it, give it to friends, add to it, or delete from it, for your own use. If you change it, please do not redistribute it. Since this list is in a constant state of revision, I would like to try to retain some kind of control over how many different versions are floating around. One thing you may not do is sell this list. I did all of the work, and you shouldn't profit from it. Remember, it's not just fair, it's the law. Also remember that it's illegal to repeat what you hear, use what you hear to aid in the commission of a crime, and it's now illegal to monitor phone calls and pagers.

As for accuracy, the standard disclaimers apply. Radio systems are continually changing, with frequencies being added, deleted, and changed. This information is as accurate as I can make it, but I can guarantee that there are mistakes in it. To make it into my list, a frequency had to be active at least once, and I needed to be reasonably certain who the user was. Some of the errors will be frequencies that have changed. Sometimes, I just leave an old frequency in the list in case it gets used again. Other changes I just don't know about. Maybe I haven't been to a location for quite some time, so I don't know of the changes there. This is the case for the few neighboring county (Kern, Ventura, etc.) freqs in the list. Some are best guesses. For instance, some of the US Air Force tactical freqs may actually be US Navy, and vice versa.

I hope you find this list useful. Questions, comments, additions, and corrections are welcome at the address at the bottom of the page.
